Right. So at this point, `err` is likely 0.  So, `damon_sysfs_turn_damon_on` will return 0 (indicating success) even if `damon_call` *fails*. Is this intentional? If `damon_call` fails, the `repeat_call_control` isn't active, but `damon_sysfs_turn_damon_on` still indicates success, and DAMON is started and running. The commit message only mentions fixing a memory leak. It doesn't discuss returning an error when `damon_call` fails. The commit is purely about fixing that leak.

